Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.320 --> 00:00:03.990
MALE SPEAKER: Thank
you all for coming.

00:00:03.990 --> 00:00:07.680
It is my pleasure to
introduce Jacob Silverman.

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:09.370
I am [INAUDIBLE].

00:00:09.370 --> 00:00:11.160
I work in new
business development

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:12.680
here in Mountain View.

00:00:12.680 --> 00:00:14.780
Jacob Silverman's
recently released book,

00:00:14.780 --> 00:00:17.950
"Terms of Service," is a
call for social media users

00:00:17.950 --> 00:00:21.120
to take back ownership
of their digital lives.

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:25.490
Integrating politics, sociology,
pop culture, and technology,

00:00:25.490 --> 00:00:27.660
Silverman explores the
surprising conformity

00:00:27.660 --> 00:00:29.430
at the heart of the
digital culture,

00:00:29.430 --> 00:00:33.440
and what it means now that
none of us can ever be alone.

00:00:33.440 --> 00:00:36.250
Reflecting on the implications
of the collapsed barriers

00:00:36.250 --> 00:00:39.530
between our private and public
lives, "Terms of Service"

00:00:39.530 --> 00:00:41.860
explains how social
media companies

00:00:41.860 --> 00:00:45.250
engineer their products to
encourage shallow engagements

00:00:45.250 --> 00:00:47.320
and discourage dissent.

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:50.560
Illuminating the new era of
connectivity as never before,

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:52.770
Silverman brings into
focus the inner conflict

00:00:52.770 --> 00:00:57.410
we feel when deciding what to
share and what to quote "like,"

00:00:57.410 --> 00:00:59.040
and explains how
we can take steps

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:00.512
we need to free ourselves.

00:01:00.512 --> 00:01:02.470
Silverman's work has been
published in "The New

00:01:02.470 --> 00:01:05.230
York Times," "The Los
Angeles Times," "Slate,"

00:01:05.230 --> 00:01:07.460
"The Atlantic,"
"The New Republic,"

00:01:07.460 --> 00:01:09.100
and many other publications.

00:01:09.100 --> 00:01:11.570
In 2008, "The Virginia
Quarterly Review"

00:01:11.570 --> 00:01:15.190
recognized him as one of the
top literary critics under 30.

00:01:15.190 --> 00:01:18.450
And in 2012-- this
is the coolest part--

00:01:18.450 --> 00:01:21.669
he was a three-time
"Jeopardy" champion.

00:01:21.669 --> 00:01:22.960
He lives in Brooklyn, New York.

00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:24.620
And I also want to
say a couple words,

00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:28.055
because I've known
Jacob for 18-plus years.

00:01:28.055 --> 00:01:31.390
